---

-generatestaticcollections:<esm> x64 by default for every plugin passed in? Note: MUST be an esm file.

Need to determine how this affects other plugins being generated for, i.e. if plugin1 has master2 and master2 has SCOLs will plugin1 need the actual NIFs from master2 when generating precombined data? It would be great if precombined data doesn't need any generated SCOL NIFs but I doubt that's the case. The main concern with all of this is with archive files and embedded .esp plugin names which are hard to deal with when it comes to the temporary esp->esm game. Update: It also appears that plugins themselves have embedded NIF paths for SCOLs (e.g. BTInteriors_Project.esp:  SCOL\BTInteriors_Project.esp\CM0013386E.NIF), so if a plugin is changed from .esp to .esm, it's still going to refer to NIFs which are only relevant to the esp version. This will definitely cause problems as -generatestaticcollections is passed the esm'ified plugin and the produced NIFs are using esm'ified paths. On top of that when -generateprecombined is used, it's also passed an esm'ified plugin and archive with relocated directories - which means the plugin is now referring to SCOL meshes that don't even exist.

This sucks but a foolproof way of handling the renamed plugins + SCOL problem is to repackage the archives with renamed dirs and if extra paranoid regenerated SCOLs.

Update to this: it appears that the path actually in the plugin doesn't really matter as far as CK is concerned, it will always default back to SCOL/<plugin>/CM<formid>.NIF and it is not editable within CK's SCOL dialog box. There's also hardcoded strings within CK itself which lend further evidence to this:

collection '%s' (%08X). Recreate and Fragment functionality for this collection will no longer function properly.
SCOL\%s\CM%08X.NIF

However this does not necessarily indicate that this is what is used as the search path - it may actually only be able generation of SCOL NIFs, but it certainly seems this location is fixed regardless of what the plugin itself says. Still, it would probably be safer to forcibly substitute this plugin path before using the esm'ified plugin with CK.

Additional data shows even vanilla esm's to have bogus SCOL filepaths:

clayne@a4-sfx:/tmp/plugin_string_dump $ find * -type f -name 'plugin.strings.all' -print0 | xargs -r0 cat | awk '{ if (match($2, "^(.+)[/\\\\]([^/\\\\]+\\.es[mpl])", a)) { utab[tolower(a[1])"/<plugin>"][a[2]]++ } }END{ for (p in utab) { printf("%s", p); for (pl in utab[p]) printf(" %s", pl); printf("\n"); } }' | sort -k1,1 | grep ^scol
