Data File Loaded 'rgo_tree_noocclude.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'BurningCampfiresThatHurt.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'America Rising - A Tale of the Enclave.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'Convenient Bridges.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'moreXplore.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'plenty 'o' exploration.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'crowdedcommonwealth.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'stumbleuponinteriors.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'InsideJobs.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'BTInteriors_Project.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'DiamondNewVendors.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'WelcometoGoodneighbor.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'SOTS.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'OutcastsAndRemnants.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'AA 50 Ways To Die.esm'...
Data File Loaded '3DNPC_FO4.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'Unofficial Fallout 4 Patch.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'AA FusionCityRising.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'AA FusionCityRising - HotC.esm'...
Data File Loaded 'BurningCampfiresThatHurt.esp.pcv.esm'...

1. A reference from Fallout4.esm was overridden and deleted in BTInteriors_Project.esp.
2. That same reference from Fallout4.esm was overridden with no changes in plenty 'o' exploration.esp.
3. In BurningCampfiresThatHurt.esp, plenty 'o' exploration.esp comes after BTInteriors_Project.esp as a master, meaning plenty 'o' exploration.esp should "win" for that same reference, effectively undoing the deletion from BTInteriors_Project.esp.
4. Since BTInteriors_Project.esp was actually loaded after plenty 'o' exploration.esp when generating the data, the deletion ended up winning and the resultant CombinedObjects.esp for BurningCampfiresThatHurt.esp has the precombined for that reference removed.
5. The same thing was tried with another reference but in that case said reference was ITM in BTInteriors_Project.esp and deleted in plenty 'o' exploration.esp. The resultant CombinedObjects.esp shows this reference's precombined data as unaffected (generated) because BTInteriors_Project.esp was actually loaded after plenty 'o' exploration.esp.

It appears that CK is using an upwards-looking DFS algorithm (i.e. resolving parent order) to load the masters and master order in the plugin does not actually matter. Normally when another master or plugin overrides a formid said formid's owner is added as a master to the overriding plugin - which usually prevents this from being an issue. However in the case of 2 different masters overriding the *same* formid, both masters will already have the same common master that owns that formid. Which master gets loaded first is purely driven by a depth first search of the plugin being loaded and the only way to enforce master1 loads before master2 is to have master1 be an explicit master of master2 - even if they're both simply overriding formids from master0.

As a final test of this, I forced plenty 'o' exploration.esp to have BTInteriors_Project.esp as a master and the original reference (which was deleted in BTInteriors_Project.esp and restored in plenty 'o' exploration.esp) showed up in CombinedObjects.esp for BurningCampfiresThatHurt.esp, which is correct per the master load order, and the other reference (which was deleted in plenty 'o' exploration.esp and restored in BTInteriors_Project.esp) showed up as removed in CombinedObjects.esp, also correct. So in short, master load order definitely matters to CK and it will not necessarily load them exactly as the target plugin dictates via the order of MAST entries.

Sigh, it would appear that timestamp has a *heavy* effect on all of this. The vanilla esms will always load in the correct order (as they're hardcoded in CK), but ensuring each master is only 1 second away from the next one (based on MAST order) results in a predictable load order everytime. However, randomizing the timestamps of every master involved results in entirely unpredictable load orders that don't even follow a timestamp sorted order.

